Final Models¶

A study of Asian Religious and Biblical Texts Data Set¶

Adrianna Grudzie, Mateusz Stczek

Data: archive.ics.uci.edu

Related article: www.researchgate.net

Introduction¶

In this task, there are 8 religious texts, 4 from Asia, 4 Biblical:

  • Upanishads,
  • Yoga Sutras,
  • Buddha Sutras,
  • Tao Te Ching,
  • Book of Wisdom,
  • Book of Proverbs,
  • Book of Ecclesiastes,
  • Book of Ecclesiasticus.

Each text has been divided into chapters (590 chapters in total) and the goal is to divide these chapters into clusters matching book of origin (or at least divide chapters into 4 religions). This notebook contains choosing the best models and visualizing the results.

Here, we load 2 dataframes. The first one is the original BoW (a Bag of Words - count of each word in each chapter) with 8000+ words. The second dataset was created by us and includes both BoW and some statistical information about each chapter such as:

  • chapter length,
  • number of sentences,
  • average sentence length,
  • number of words (without stopwords),
  • number of unique words (without stopwords),
  • average word length,
  • chapter complexity (flesch reading ease),
  • positive/negative/neutral tinting of chapter.

def get_clustering_metric_scores(data,model,metric,n_clusters):
    # if(model.__name__=='GaussianMixture'):
    #     return [metric(data,
    #                 model(n_components=k).fit_predict(data)) 
    #             for k in n_clusters]
    # else:
    return [metric(data,
                model(k).fit_predict(data)) 
            for k in n_clusters]

def plot_metrics(data, model, 
            metrics=[silhouette_score, davies_bouldin_score, calinski_harabasz_score], 
            clusters=list(range(2,11))):

    len_metrics = len(metrics)
    ncols = min(3,len_metrics)
    nrows = len_metrics / ncols
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=[ncols*4,nrows*3])
    for i in range(len_metrics):
        plt.subplot(nrows, ncols, i + 1)
        plt.title(f"{str(metrics[i].__name__).replace('_', ' ')}")
        scores = get_clustering_metric_scores(data, model, metrics[i], clusters)
        plt.plot(clusters, scores)
    plt.show()

Summary¶

Overall, model selection is equally important as feature engineering. In our opinion, the best way of clustering these 590 chapters into groups is by using KMeans or Agglomerative Clustering with 2 clusters.

After working with this dataset we have learned a few things about unsupervised clustering. One of them is that PCA drastically changes the results (usually for the better) and greatly reduces size of data to work on.

What's more, even the knowledge of the original number of clusters in this task did not help recreating the original 8 books from 589 chapters. Instead, the best we could do is to separate chapters from Christian religion from texts originating in eastern religions.

Visualization of the results¶

We present 3 visualizations. The first one is a simple KMeans with 2 clusters. Next one is more unexpected - Gaussian Mixture Model with 9 clusters. The last one is Agglomerative clustering for 3 clusters. For each visualization there are 2 scatterplots: one is showing real labels and the other clustering results.

Finally, for each of these 3 clusterings there is a plot showing the percentage of each original label present in each created cluster. In other words, it's the percentage of all chapters from a given book clustered in each cluster for our clustering solutions.

def scatterplot_compare(data, labels_original, labels_predicted):
    df_reduced = PCA(n_components=2, whiten=True).fit_transform(data)

    t1 = pd.DataFrame({'x': df_reduced[:, 0], 
                        'y': df_reduced[:, 1], 
                        'Original label': labels_original})
    t2 = pd.DataFrame({'x': df_reduced[:, 0], 
                        'y': df_reduced[:, 1], 
                        'Predicted label': labels_predicted})

    fig = plt.figure(figsize=[9,4])
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    plt.title('Original labels')
    sns.scatterplot(data=t1, x='x', y='y', hue='Original label')
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    plt.title('Clustering results')
    sns.scatterplot(data=t2, x='x', y='y', hue='Predicted label')
    plt.show() 

def get_clusters_percentage(correct_labels, predicted_labels):
    vcounts = correct_labels.value_counts()
    cluster_ids = predicted_labels.unique()
    df_vcounts = pd.DataFrame(columns=['YogaSutra',
                                    'Upanishad',
                                    'TaoTeChing',
                                    'BookOfEccleasiasticus',
                                    'Buddhism',
                                    'BookOfProverb',
                                    'BookOfWisdom',
                                    'BookOfEcclesiastes'])
    for k in cluster_ids:
        df_vcounts = df_vcounts.append(correct_labels[predicted_labels == k].value_counts())
    df_vcounts.index=cluster_ids
    df_vcounts = df_vcounts/vcounts
    df_vcounts.fillna(0, inplace=True)
    return df_vcounts.transpose()

def plot_clusters_barplots(correct_labels, predicted_labels):
    df_percentages = get_clusters_percentage(correct_labels, predicted_labels)
    ncols = len(df_percentages)
    nrows = len(df_percentages.columns)
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=[ncols,nrows*4])
    for i in range(nrows):
        plt.subplot(nrows, 1, i + 1)
        plt.title(f"Book percentages in {i}th predicted cluster")
        tmp = pd.DataFrame(data=[df_percentages.iloc[:,i].index, df_percentages.iloc[:,i]]).transpose()
        tmp.columns = ['Original book', 'Percentage of each book in this cluster']
        tmp
        sns.barplot(data=tmp,
                    x='Original book',
                    y= 'Percentage of each book in this cluster')
        plt.xticks(rotation=70)
        plt.ylim(0,1)
        plt.tick_params(labelbottom=False)
        plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4)
    plt.tick_params(labelbottom=True)
    plt.show()
